            <h2 id="how-cold">1) How cold was it in Houston during the January 25, 2026 storm?</h2>
            <p>
              Houston’s cold wasn’t “cute.” It was the kind of cold that turns routine life into a high-friction hazard.
              Local reporting noted an <strong>Extreme Cold Warning</strong> in effect across Southeast Texas into <strong>Tuesday, January 27, 2026</strong>,
              with morning temperatures in the <strong>teens and 20s</strong> and wind that made it feel even colder.
              Winds of roughly <strong>10–20 mph</strong> (with higher gusts) were reported in forecasts, driving wind chills down into single digits/low teens in the Houston area,
              and even lower in outlying regions.
            </p>

            <div class="quote" role="note" aria-label="Why wind chill matters">
              <p>
                🧠 Wind chill is the “feels-like” effect of wind stripping heat from skin. In practical terms: it accelerates hypothermia risk for anyone outside without adequate shelter.
              </p>
            </div>

            <p>
              That’s the key: it’s not just the thermometer — it’s <em>exposure time</em>. If you’re housed, you can “wait it out.”
              If you’re unsheltered, you are running a survival calculation against the clock.
            </p>

            <h2 id="shutdown">2) How did the storm shut Houston down?</h2>
            <p>
              “Shutdown” in Houston usually looks like a cascading series of safety decisions: avoid travel, close public-facing services, cancel events, delay openings, and reduce risk.
              On <strong>Sunday, January 25</strong>, multiple outlets tracked the expanding list of closures and changes heading into <strong>Monday, January 26, 2026</strong>.
              The reasons were simple: <strong>ice risk</strong>, <strong>unsafe roads</strong> (especially bridges/overpasses), and <strong>extreme cold exposure</strong>.
            </p>

            <h3 id="closures">Examples of closures & delays (Jan 26, 2026)</h3>
            <p>
              City and county offices, destinations, and services posted closures and delayed openings for Monday. Public notices and local reporting listed impacted operations
              (including county offices and major attractions) as conditions remained hazardous.
            </p>

            <div class="callout" style="border-color:rgba(111,231,255,.26)">
              <div class="title"><span class="dot" style="background:var(--cyan); box-shadow:0 0 0 6px rgba(111,231,255,.18)" aria-hidden="true"></span>Operational reality check</div>
              <ul class="bullets">
                <li>When Houston “shuts down,” it’s not symbolic — it’s a safety throttle on movement, staffing, and travel.</li>
                <li>Ice + bridges + low temps = wreck risk, emergency response delays, and secondary hazards.</li>
                <li>Everyone slows down. But not everyone has a place to slow down <em>inside</em>.</li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <h2 id="warming-centers">3) The city opened resources. Why were people still at risk?</h2>
            <p>
              The City of Houston announced <strong>12 warming centers</strong> ahead of the cold snap and confirmed they remained open during the storm window.
              That matters. It saves lives.
            </p>

            <p>
              But a deadly truth survives every freeze: <strong>availability is not the same as reachability</strong>.
              People sleeping outside may not receive alerts in time, may not have transportation, may avoid shelters due to safety concerns,
              may lack documentation, may fear separation from partners or pets, or may simply be too far from the nearest site when roads and temps turn hostile.
              So even when the city activates resources, the system can still leave people exposed.
            </p>

            <h2 id="why-homelessness">4) Why January 25, 2026 becomes a homelessness issue (fast)</h2>
            <p>
              Extreme cold is a multiplier. It turns existing vulnerability into immediate danger.
              Greater Houston’s homelessness numbers show why “weather events” can become “fatal events” when too many people live unsheltered.
              The Coalition for the Homeless of Houston/Harris County reported that the <strong>2025 Point-in-Time Count</strong> identified
              <strong>3,325 people experiencing homelessness</strong>, including <strong>1,282 unsheltered</strong>.
            </p>

            <p>
              Another signal: research reporting has highlighted reduced shelter bed availability in the region, while unsheltered homelessness rose —
              a reminder that capacity + flow to housing matters, especially during severe weather windows.
            </p>

